spec: ab3451
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 677 (ab3451): __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__ dict-presence checks for abc module types."
    - "Theme: __getitem__/__setitem__/__delitem__ dict-presence (obj[key], obj[key]=val, del obj[key])."
    - "All values False — abc types are abstract base class machinery with no custom getitem/setitem/delitem defined in their own __dict__."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__getitem__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __getitem__. obj[key] delegates to __getitem__ when defined in the class's own __dict__. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class convenience wrapper with no __getitem__ in its own __dict__. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration; subscript access has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities and __getitem__ is absent from ABCMeta.__dict__. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __getitem__ in its own __dict__ — functions are callables and descriptors; subscript access is not meaningful for function objects. Wave 656 (ab3136) already confirmed __getitem__ is false for all 3 abc subjects."
    - "Key finding (__setitem__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __setitem__. obj[key]=val delegates to __setitem__ when defined in the class's own __dict__. abc.ABC: no __setitem__ in its own __dict__; item assignment raises TypeError by default. abc.ABCMeta: does not define __setitem__ in ABCMeta.__dict__; the metaclass's API surface (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__) has no item assignment component. The function type: functions define no __setitem__ in their own __dict__; item assignment to a function object raises TypeError at runtime. Wave 657 (ab3151) already confirmed __setitem__ is false for all 3 abc subjects."
    - "Key finding (__delitem__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __delitem__. del obj[key] delegates to __delitem__ when defined in the class's own __dict__. abc.ABC: no __delitem__ in its own __dict__; del obj[key] raises TypeError by default. abc.ABCMeta: does not define __delitem__ in ABCMeta.__dict__. The function type: functions define no ordering or deletion protocol in their own __dict__; del f[key] raises TypeError at runtime. Wave 657 (ab3151) already confirmed __delitem__ is false for all 3 abc subjects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — consistent with the all-false pattern for container/mapping dunders first tested in waves 656 (__getitem__) and 657 (__setitem__, __delitem__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __getitem__, __setitem__, and __delitem__ (at the dict-contains level) — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every dunder tested across 26 consecutive waves (652–677). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery — not operator overloading, comparison, display, or container/mapping protocol overrides."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 669 (ab3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 670 (ab3346): __neg__/__pos__/__abs__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 671 (ab3361): __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 672 (ab3376): __trunc__/__round__/__index__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 673 (ab3391): __int__/__float__/__complex__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 674 (ab3406): __bool__/__str__/__repr__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 675 (ab3421): __hash__/__eq__/__lt__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 676 (ab3436): __le__/__gt__/__ge__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 677 (ab3451): __getitem__/__setitem__/__delitem__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __getitem__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__getitem__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __getitem__.
# obj[key] delegates to __getitem__ when defined in the class's own __dict__.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no __getitem__
#   in its own __dict__. obj[key] raises TypeError by default since object
#   provides no __getitem__.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. __getitem__ is absent from ABCMeta.__dict__ — the metaclass's
#   API surface (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__) has no
#   subscript access component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __getitem__ in their own __dict__. obj[key] on a
#   function object raises TypeError at runtime. Wave 656 (ab3136) first
#   confirmed this result.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3451.getitem:
  description: "abc types __getitem__ dict-presence checks; wave 677"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3451

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3451001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__getitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3451002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__getitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3451003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__getitem__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __setitem__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__setitem__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __setitem__.
# obj[key]=val delegates to __setitem__ when defined in the class's own __dict__.
# abc.ABC: no __setitem__ in its own __dict__; obj[key]=val raises TypeError
#   by default since object does not define __setitem__.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __setitem__ in ABCMeta.__dict__. The metaclass
#   is focused on abstract method registration and subclass checking, not item
#   assignment. Wave 657 (ab3151) first confirmed this result.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __setitem__ in their own __dict__. f[key]=val
#   raises TypeError at runtime since object provides no __setitem__.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151) first confirmed this result.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3451.setitem:
  description: "abc types __setitem__ dict-presence checks; wave 677"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3451

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3451004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__setitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3451005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__setitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3451006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__setitem__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __delitem__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__delitem__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __delitem__.
# del obj[key] delegates to __delitem__ when defined in the class's own __dict__.
# abc.ABC: no __delitem__ in its own __dict__; del obj[key] raises TypeError
#   by default since object does not define __delitem__.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __delitem__ in ABCMeta.__dict__. The metaclass
#   is focused on abstract method registration and subclass checking, not item
#   deletion. Wave 657 (ab3151) first confirmed this result.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __delitem__ in their own __dict__. del f[key]
#   raises TypeError at runtime since object provides no __delitem__.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151) first confirmed this result.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

